}\n|-\n|US [[Cashbox (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19740309.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 3/09/74 |website=Tropicalglen.com |date=1974-03-09 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184743/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19740309.html |archive-date=2018-01-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1974)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia<ref name=\"australian-charts.com\">{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=40275 |title=Forum - Top 100 End of Year AMR Charts - 1980s (ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts) |website=Australian-charts.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3893a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3893a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3893a |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Denmark<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|Netherlands<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|South Africa<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|Switzerland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/charts/jahreshitparade/1974|title=Swiss Year-End Charts 1974 - swisscharts.com|first=Steffen|last=Hung|date=|website=swisscharts.com|accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-charts.top-source.info/top-100-1974.shtml |title=Top 100 1974 - UK Music Charts |website=Uk-charts.top-source.info |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1974.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1974/Top 100 Songs of 1974 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1974YESP.html |title=Cash Box YE Pop Singles - 1974 |website=Tropicalglen.com |date=1974-12-28 |accessdate=2016-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009212559/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/1974YESP.html |archive-date=2016-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|}\n\n====All-time charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1958-2018)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100-60th-anniversary |title=Billboard Hot 100 60th Anniversary |website=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|220\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n====Other versions====\n*The first recording of the English-language version (lyrics by McKuen) was released on 1963 album ''[[Time to Think (The Kingston Trio album)|Time to Think]]'' by [[The Kingston Trio]].<ref name=\"AM-Eder\">{{cite web |last1=Eder |first1=Bruce |title=The Kingston Trio - Time to Think |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/time-to-think-mw0000859317 |website=AllMusic |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n*[[The Fortunes]] recorded the song for a 1968 single.\n*[[Colombia]]n duet [[Ana y Jaime]] released a Spanish version called ''Estaciones en el Sol''.\n*Pearls Before Swine included a version of the song on their album City of Gold in 1971, with lyrics reflecting the darkness of Brel's original version.\n*A cover version by [[Bobby Wright]] reached the Top 40 of the ''[[Billboard magazine]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|Hot Country Singles]] chart in 1974.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/country-songs|title=Country Music: Top Country Songs Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n*Hong Kong English pop and Cantopop band [[The Wynners]] cover version in 1974 album [[Listen to the Wynners]] and [[Alan Tam]] as the vocal.\n*[[Too Much Joy]] recorded the song for their 1988 album ''Son Of Sam I Am'', and it became a regular part of their live shows.\n*[[Westlife]] made their cover version in 1999 and included it on their album [[Westlife (album)|Westlife]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-seasonsinthesun.ogg|2005-12-10}}\n* [http://www.superseventies.com/1974_3singles.html ''Seasons in the Sun''] at Super Seventies.\n* [http://www.brelitude.net/Covers/chansons/moribond.htm \"List of 'Le Moribond' covers\"], Brelitude.net\n* [http://www.slate.com/id/2114863/ \"Goodbye, Papa, It's Hard to Die: The enduring appeal of an abominable pop song\"] ([[Slate.com]], March 16, 2005)\n* {{MetroLyrics song|andy-williams|seasons-in-the-sun|version=Andy Williams cover}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Jacques Brel}}\n{{Westlife songs}}\n{{UK Christmas No. 1s in the 1990s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seasons in the Sun}}\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:1973 singles]]\n[[Category:1974 singles]]\n[[Category:1999 singles]]\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jacques Brel]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Rod McKuen]]\n[[Category:Jacques Brel songs]]\n[[Category:The Kingston Trio songs]]\n[[Category:Vikingarna (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Westlife songs]]\n[[Category:Nirvana (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about death]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Wright songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Bell Records singles]]\n[[Category:Philips Records singles]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Single of the Year singles]]\n[[Category:Christmas number-one singles in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Translated song; English adaptation of \"Le moribond\"}}\n{{for|the 2012 book about British history|Dominic Sandbrook}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Le Moribond\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     = song\n| artist   = [[Jacques Brel]]\n| album    = [[Marieke (album)|Marieke]]\n| released = 1961\n| format   =\n| recorded = February 22, 1961\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Chanson]]\n| length   = 3:06\n| label    = [[Philips Records|Philips]]\n| writer   = [[Jacques Brel]]\n| producer =\n}}\n\n\"'''Seasons in the Sun'''\" is an English-language adaptation of the 1961 song \"'''Le Moribond'''\" by Belgian singer-songwriter [[Jacques Brel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2008/12/brel-d15.html |title=30 years since the death of Jacques Brel: his life, his art, his legacy |publisher=World Socialist Web Site |date=December 2008 |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> with lyrics rewritten in 1963 by American singer-poet [[Rod McKuen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rodmckuen.org/flights/080400.htm |quote=My first experience with Brel consisted of doing an unauthorized adaptation of 'Le Moribund', which I called 'Seasons in the Sun'... I subsequently learned that Brel had received my recording... |first=Rod |last=McKuen |title=Remembering Jacques Brel |date=April 8, 2000 |work=Flight Plan |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> portraying a dying man's farewell to his loved ones. It became a worldwide [[song|hit]] in 1974 for Canadian singer [[Terry Jacks]] and became a [[List of UK Singles Chart Christmas number ones|Christmas number one in the UK]] in 1999 for [[Westlife]].\n\n==Terry Jacks recording==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Seasons in the Sun\n| cover      = Seasons_in_the_Sun_-_Terry_Jacks.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Terry Jacks]]\n| album      = [[Seasons in the Sun (album)|Seasons in the Sun]]\n| B-side     = Put the Bone In\n| released   = December 1973\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1973\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 3:24\n| label      = [[Bell Records|Bell]]\n| writer     = [[Jacques Brel]], [[Rod McKuen]]\n| producer   = [[Terry Jacks]]\n| prev_title = Concrete Sea\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[If You Go Away]]\n| next_year  = 1974\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|-tPcc1ftj8E|\"Seasons in the Sun\"}}}}\n}}\nTerry Jacks recorded \"Seasons in the Sun\" in [[Vancouver]] in 1973 with his then-wife [[Susan Jacks]]. They made the decision to record the song when [[The Beach Boys]], who had recorded a version with Terry Jacks producing, decided to abandon their recording.\n\nJacks released his version as a single in 1973 on his own label, Goldfish Records. \"Put the Bone In\", an original composition about burying a deceased pet dog, was included as the B-side. The single soon topped the record charts in the U.S. (where it was released on [[Bell Records (1950s-70s)|Bell Records]]), in Canada, and the UK,<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 299}}</ref> selling over 14 million copies worldwide.\n\nJacks's version was released in the United States in December 1973, and made the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] a month later. On March 2, 1974, the song began a three-week run at number one atop the Hot 100, and remained in the top 40 until almost [[Memorial Day]] weekend.  Jacks's version also spent one week on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary|Easy Listening]] charts.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top Adult Contemporary: 1961-2001|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2002 |publisher=Record Research |page=123}}</ref> ''Billboard'' ranked it as the number two song for 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobborst.com/popculture/songoftheyear/ |title=Number One Song of the Year: 1946-2015 |website=bobborst.com |access-date=August 22, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420175438/http://www.bobborst.com/popculture/songoftheyear/ |archive-date=April 20, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Although he released several other singles that were moderately successful in Canada, \"Seasons in the Sun\" would become Jacks's only major solo hit in the United States.<ref>Whitburn, Joel, \"Top Pop Hits: 1955-2006, 2007.</ref> In Canada, the single (Gold Fish GF 100) reached number one on the [[RPM (magazine)|RPM Magazine]] charts January 26, 1974, and remained there four weeks.\n\nThough the song enjoyed contemporary success, modern criticism takes a dimmer view, considering it overly sentimentalized. Jacks's version has been held up as an example of bad music, such as having been listed as [[List of music considered the worst|one of the worst pop songs ever recorded]] and ranking number five in a similar CNN poll in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|author=Todd Leopold |url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/SHOWBIZ/Music/04/25/worst.songs/index.html |title=The worst song of all time, part II - Apr 26, 2006 |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-01}}</ref>\n\nJacks also released a German-language version in Germany with lyrics by Gerd M\u00fcller-Schwanke, \"In den G\u00e4rten der Zeit\".<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/2008249 \"In den G\u00e4rten der Zeit\"] at 45cat.com</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1973\u201374)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report|KMR]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |title=Australian Chart Book |website=Austchartbook.com.au |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|1|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|2|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']] Top Singles<ref name=\"tsort1\">{{cite web|url=http://tsort.info/music/9e4un2.htm |title=Song artist 781 - Terry Jacks |website=Tsort.info |date= |accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']] Adult Contemporary\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Denmark<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|France<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|1|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=Seasons in the Sun|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|7|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|1|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref name=\"tsort1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|1|song=Seasons in the Sun|artist=Terry Jacks}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=1453#n_view_location |title=flavour of new zealand - search listener |website=Flavourofnz.co.nz |date